{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>This entry represents D-alanyl carrier protein DltC, which is part of the operon for incorporation of D-Ala residues into lipoteichoic acids (LTAs), which requires the activity of four gene products (DltA to DltD). DltA is a cytoplasmic D-alanine-D-alanyl carrier protein ligase that catalyses the D-alanylation of the D-alanyl carrier protein DltC (or Dcp); DltB is a transmembrane protein thought to be involved in the efflux of activated D-alanine to the site of acylation; and DltD is thought to be a membrane-associated protein that may have multifunctional activities (hydrolysis of mischarged DltC, facilitation of D-alanine ligation to DltC and D-alanylation of LTAs) [[cite:PUB00086797], [cite:PUB00086696]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false} {"text" "<p>These proteins are involved in the biosynthesis of D-alanyl-lipoteichoic acid in bacteria. They are major wall and membrane components of most Gram-positive bacteria [[cite:PUB00043379]]. Streptococcus pneumoniae is one of the few species of low-G and C Gram-positive bacteria that do not contain d-alanine in teichoic acids [[cite:PUB00043380]]. d-alanine residues are thought to protect this human pathogen against the actions of cationic antimicrobial peptides. Mammals use antimicrobial peptides to protect themselves from invasive infectious agents such as Group A streptococcus (GAS), which causes necrotising fasciitis and toxic shock syndrome [[cite:PUB00043381]]. Teichoic acids and D-alanylation of teichoic acids are required for colony spreading in Staphylococcus aureus [[cite:PUB00043382]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "7r49", "name" "Crystal structure of the L. plantarum acyl carrier protein synthase (AcpS)in complex with D-alanyl carrier protein (DltC1)"}, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR036736", "name" "ACP-like superfamily", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :membe